key_points: Over 100 marchers protested in Milwaukee against the not guilty verdict of Kyle Rittenhouse, who killed two and wounded one during Kenosha protests in 2020.
The protest was in response to Rittenhouse's acquittal for the shootings during the unrest following the police shooting of Jacob Blake.
Mariah Smith of the Peoples Revolution emphasized the verdict's impact on white allies in the Black liberation movement.
The Milwaukee Alliance Against Racist and Political Repression sponsored the march, ending at the Federal Courthouse where speeches were given.
Protesters chanted slogans like "No Justice No Peace No Racist Police" and "Black Lives Matter."
Omar Flores, alliance co-chair, stressed the importance of organized action for civilian control of the police.
Retired minister Dale Stohre expressed grief over the verdict and its implications for all involved, including the town of Kenosha.
Milwaukee resident Nathaniel Haack pointed out the chilling effect of the verdict on the right to protest peacefully.
Kenosha resident Adelana Akindes criticized the portrayal of protesters as rioters and looters by the judge overseeing Rittenhouse's case.
Participants viewed the verdict as a setback for racial justice and the safety of protestors.
spokespersons: Omar Flores (Co-chair, Milwaukee Alliance Against Racist and Political Repression)
Adelana Akindes (Participant, Students for a Democratic Society)
